<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-625-598  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 625 598.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  June 1990 v22 n6 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM: strategies for the 90's. (includes related article on IBM'splans to consolidate its operating systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Snider, Harold.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM's plan for developing its mainframe computer systems in the1990s calls for improved methods of memory management and forcomputers and programming techniques which take advantage of theseimprovements.andP;  IBM's Summit mainframes, expected to be announcedin 1991, use System Application Architecture (SAA) and ExpandedStorage Architecture (ESA), which speeds processing by separatingdata from applications.andP;  ESA allows for Single Level Storage(SLS), in which various storage devices are managed automaticallyby the computer system rather than by individual applications.andO;The system optimizes I/O by storing most-used data in quicklyaccessed storage, such as main memory, while storing seldom useddata on slower devices, such as tape drives.andP;  IBM is upgrading itsproduct line gradually to integrate the line with its FSspecifications.andP;  SAA, the MVS operating system and SQL - atechnique for manipulating data without specifying I/O methods -are recent developments in IBM's strategy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Computer DesignMemory ManagementProduct DevelopmentStrategic PlanningMainframe ComputersI-O Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>